//! # 练习 9: `unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn` — R:
//! # Exercise 9: `unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn` — unsafe function body specification for Rust 2024 (Rust 1.95)
//! 
//! **Difficulty**: Medium
//! **Test points**: `unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn` lint, Rust 2024 behavior changes, unsafe block granularity control
//! 
//! ## Background
//! 
//! In Rust 2021 and earlier, the function body of `unsafe fn` is treated as an implicit `unsafe` block:
//! All unsafe operations in the function body can be written directly without additional wrapping `unsafe {}`.
//! 
//! There is a problem with this design: it blurs the caller's unsafe and the implementer's unsafe.  
//! `unsafe fn` marks "calling this function requires unsafe permission",
//! But it does not mean "all operations in the implementation of this function automatically obtain unsafe permissions".
//! 
//! Rust 2024 (which enables `unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn` by default) changes this:
//! The function body of `unsafe fn` is safe by default, and the internal unsafe operations still need to be explicitly wrapped in an `unsafe {}` block.
//! This makes the boundaries of unsafe clearer and every line of unsafe code is clearly visible.
//! 
//! ## Requirements
//! 
//! - Understand the difference between `unsafe fn` (call constraints) and `unsafe {}` (permission grant)
//! - Rewrote Rust 2021 style `unsafe fn` to Rust 2024 style
//! - Proper use of minimal-granularity `unsafe {}` blocks within unsafe fn bodies

