//! # Exercise 1: Raw pointers and safe array splitting
//! 
//! **Difficulty**: Medium
//! **Test points**: Creation, offset, and dereference of raw pointers; interaction with the borrow checker
//! 
//! ## Title description
//! 
//! `slice::split_at_mut` in the standard library can be used in scenarios where the borrow checker fails to pass during compilation.
//! Safely split a mutable slice into two non-overlapping parts.
//! 
//! Please implement an equivalent `safe_split_at_mut` function using **raw pointers** (`*mut T`).
//! 
//! ## Requirements
//! 
//! - Use `as_mut_ptr()` to get the raw pointer of the slice
//! - Use `pointer::add` for pointer offset
//! - Convert raw pointer back to slice using `slice::from_raw_parts_mut`
//! - Make sure all unsafe operations are wrapped in an `unsafe` block
//! - The function itself is safe, the caller does not need to write `unsafe`
//! 
//! ## Tips
//! 
//! - Raw pointers are not subject to the borrow checker, so multiple raw pointers pointing to different locations in the same array can exist at the same time
//! - You need to use assertions to ensure `mid <= slice.len()`, otherwise a panic will be triggered (this is the contract of the safe API)

